<p>Let r(t) be a vector-valued function such that r(t) = &lt;x(t), y(t), z(t)&gt; &forall; t &isin; &#x211d; for arbitrary functions x(t), y(t), z(t): &#x211d; &rarr; &#x211d;</p>  <p>||r(t)|| &equiv; &Sqrt;(x(t)&sup2; + y(t)&sup2; + z(t)&sup2;) &forall; t &isin; &#x211d;</p>  <p>For r(t) to be considered a unit vector, ||r(t)|| = 1 &forall; t &isin; &#x211d;</p>  <p>&rArr; &Sqrt;(x(t)&sup2; + y(t)&sup2; + z(t)&sup2;) = 1 &forall; t &isin; &#x211d;</p>  <p>&rArr; x(t)&sup2; + y(t)&sup2; + z(t)&sup2; = 1 &forall; t &isin; &#x211d;</p>  <p>My question:</p>  <p>Is it possible to prove, given arbitrary functions x(t), y(t), z(t): &#x211d; &rarr; &#x211d;, that r(t) is a unit vector &forall; t &isin; &#x211d;?</p>  <p>For example: </p>  <p>Say r(t) = &lt;cos(t), sin(t), 0&gt; we can solve this problem easily:</p>  <p>cos&sup2;(t) + sin&sup2;(t) + 0&sup2; = 1</p>  <p>However, if r(t) = &lt;3, 2t, cos(t)> then r(t) is not a unit vector:</p>  <p>3&sup2; + 4t&sup2; + cos&sup2;(t) &ge; 9 &forall; t</p>  <p>I need a way to determine if r(t) is  a unit vector for any x(t), y(t), z(t): &#x211d; &rarr; &#x211d;</p>